    33Ôćĺ/// A value in a key-value.
    34Ôćĺ///
    35Ôćĺ/// Values are an anonymous bag containing some structured datum.
    36Ôćĺ///
    37Ôćĺ/// # Capturing values
    38Ôćĺ///
    39Ôćĺ/// There are a few ways to capture a value:
    40Ôćĺ///
    41Ôćĺ/// - Using the `Value::from_*` methods.
    42Ôćĺ/// - Using the `ToValue` trait.
    43Ôćĺ/// - Using the standard `From` trait.
    44Ôćĺ///
    45Ôćĺ/// ## Using the `Value::from_*` methods
    46Ôćĺ///
    47Ôćĺ/// `Value` offers a few constructor methods that capture values of different kinds.
    48Ôćĺ///
    49Ôćĺ/// ```
    50Ôćĺ/// use log::kv::Value;
    51Ôćĺ///
    52Ôćĺ/// let value = Value::from_debug(&42i32);
    53Ôćĺ///
    54Ôćĺ/// assert_eq!(None, value.to_i64());
    55Ôćĺ/// ```
    56Ôćĺ///
    57Ôćĺ/// ## Using the `ToValue` trait
    58Ôćĺ///
    59Ôćĺ/// The `ToValue` trait can be used to capture values generically.
    60Ôćĺ/// It's the bound used by `Source`.
    61Ôćĺ///
    62Ôćĺ/// ```
    63Ôćĺ/// # use log::kv::ToValue;
    64Ôćĺ/// let value = 42i32.to_value();
    65Ôćĺ///
    66Ôćĺ/// assert_eq!(Some(42), value.to_i64());
    67Ôćĺ/// ```
    68Ôćĺ///
    69Ôćĺ/// ## Using the standard `From` trait
    70Ôćĺ///
    71Ôćĺ/// Standard types that implement `ToValue` also implement `From`.
    72Ôćĺ///
    73Ôćĺ/// ```
    74Ôćĺ/// use log::kv::Value;
    75Ôćĺ///
    76Ôćĺ/// let value = Value::from(42i32);
    77Ôćĺ///
    78Ôćĺ/// assert_eq!(Some(42), value.to_i64());
    79Ôćĺ/// ```
    80Ôćĺ///
    81Ôćĺ/// # Data model
    82Ôćĺ///
    83Ôćĺ/// Values can hold one of a number of types:
    84Ôćĺ///
    85Ôćĺ/// - **Null:** The absence of any other meaningful value. Note that
    86Ôćĺ///   `Some(Value::null())` is not the same as `None`. The former is
    87Ôćĺ///   `null` while the latter is `undefined`. This is important to be
    88Ôćĺ///   able to tell the difference between a key-value that was logged,
    89Ôćĺ///   but its value was empty (`Some(Value::null())`) and a key-value
    90Ôćĺ///   that was never logged at all (`None`).
    91Ôćĺ/// - **Strings:** `str`, `char`.
    92Ôćĺ/// - **Booleans:** `bool`.
    93Ôćĺ/// - **Integers:** `u8`-`u128`, `i8`-`i128`, `NonZero*`.
    94Ôćĺ/// - **Floating point numbers:** `f32`-`f64`.
    95Ôćĺ/// - **Errors:** `dyn (Error + 'static)`.
    96Ôćĺ/// - **`serde`:** Any type in `serde`'s data model.
    97Ôćĺ/// - **`sval`:** Any type in `sval`'s data model.
    98Ôćĺ///
    99Ôćĺ/// # Serialization
   100Ôćĺ///
   101Ôćĺ/// Values provide a number of ways to be serialized.
   102Ôćĺ///
   103Ôćĺ/// For basic types the [`Value::visit`] method can be used to extract the
   104Ôćĺ/// underlying typed value. However, this is limited in the amount of types
   105Ôćĺ/// supported (see the [`VisitValue`] trait methods).
   106Ôćĺ///
   107Ôćĺ/// For more complex types one of the following traits can be used:
   108Ôćĺ///  * `sval::Value`, requires the `kv_sval` feature.
   109Ôćĺ///  * `serde::Serialize`, requires the `kv_serde` feature.
   110Ôćĺ///
   111Ôćĺ/// You don't need a visitor to serialize values through `serde` or `sval`.
   112Ôćĺ///
   113Ôćĺ/// A value can always be serialized using any supported framework, regardless
   114Ôćĺ/// of how it was captured. If, for example, a value was captured using its
   115Ôćĺ/// `Display` implementation, it will serialize through `serde` as a string. If it was
   116Ôćĺ/// captured as a struct using `serde`, it will also serialize as a struct
   117Ôćĺ/// through `sval`, or can be formatted using a `Debug`-compatible representation.
   118Ôćĺ#[derive(Clone)]
   119Ôćĺpub struct Value<'v> {
